  "summary": "In a room in Dover, Theodora and Richard engage in a tense confrontation. Theodora accuses Richard of orchestrating a scheme that required her to meet Vincent Easton alone at night, dressed specifically to manipulate Easton into a deal for incriminating files. She realizes that Richard was willing to sacrifice her reputation to protect his own safety and interests. Theodora further reveals that she had actually left with Vincent Easton three days prior, contradicting the story the servants gave Richard about her trip to the countryside. Although Richard attempts to offer forgiveness, Theodora refuses, citing his infidelity and his recent betrayal. She declares her intention to leave for her freedom and exits the house.\n\nIn a separate scene, a man wearing a dark coat arrives at a residence on Calver Street during cold, snowy weather. He asks Mrs. Casey for \"Madame Lion\" and whistles the tune of \"Three Blind Mice\" as he climbs the stairs.\n\nMeanwhile, Molly Davis observes a new sign for the \"Monksville Manor Guest House.\" She reflects on her husband Jiles's talents as they prepare for their new business venture. Following the death of Aunt Katherine, Molly inherited Monkswell Manor. Because the couple could not find a smaller residence and struggled with the manor's bulky Victorian furniture, they decided to operate the house as a guesthouse. A lawyer notes that the property is in good condition due to extensive renovations performed by the late Miss Emery before the war.",
